Caption: When I became one with the bassline electronic music gave me a whole new meaning to life, it has saved me from suicidal thoughts, it has become my passion sometime before I got through high school. Caption:
There is still time to join our Summer Audio Meditation Series!! 

Let rest be your medicine for a healthful summer and the foundation of your self-care practices.

Weekly series that ends September 5th 

Amid the heat and activity of the summer months, reserve time for quiet, stillness, and rest. In this season of growth, consider yourself and your inner landscape a garden. Practicing stillness allows us the opportunity to listen deeply to our internal dialogue and become the observer fully engaged and present in our lives. What would we like to grow and nurture this season? Rest is an essential ingredient for our health and wellness as human beings, taking a respite from doing, and allowing what is true for us to arise.

Details:
â€¢The Summer Siesta Recorded Weekly Meditation Series is offered by Judy Bousquin through Yoga Moves
â€¢This weekly series begins July 11 and sojourns through September 5
â€¢Investment in yourself and your meditation practice: $29
â€¢All meditations are original creations that are downloaded onto your favorite device to listen whenever and how often you want to practice
â€¢No experience is necessary; seasoned and new meditators welcome

Each week you will receive:
â€¢One guided meditation
â€¢One silent meditation with a prompt
â€¢One poem
â€¢A writing prompt
â€¢Resources when available

Your meditations will arrive weekly in your email inbox from Judy
at healingandrenewal@gmail.com, the morning of the expected date, each Tuesday between 7/11 â€“ 9/5/2023

You will have ongoing access to your teacher, Judy Bousquin
As these meditations are recorded, take your practice wherever you go. For questions, reach out to Judy through yogamoves02180@gmail.com with Summer Meditation Series in the subject line.

Caption:
Meditation has been shown to be effective in reducing anxiety for a number of reasons. Here are some of the ways in which meditation can help an anxious mind:
ğŸŒ¸Calming the nervous system: Anxiety is often accompanied by physical symptoms such as rapid breathing, increased heart rate, and muscle tension. Meditation can help to calm the nervous system, reducing these physical symptoms and promoting a sense of relaxation and calm.
ğŸŒ¸Focusing the mind: An anxious mind is often characterized by racing thoughts and a sense of overwhelm. Meditation can help to quiet the mind and bring focus to the present moment, reducing feelings of stress and anxiety.
ğŸŒ¸Developing awareness: Meditation can help to develop an awareness of our thoughts and emotions, allowing us to observe them without judgment or reaction. This can help to reduce the intensity of anxious thoughts and feelings and promote a sense of peace and equanimity.
ğŸŒ¸Building resilience: Regular meditation practice can help to build resilience and coping skills, making it easier to navigate stressful situations and manage anxiety in the long term.

Caption:
Our mental health determines how well we lead our lives. According to the National Mental Health Survey of India 2015-2016, nearly 15% of the Indian population, or roughly 197 million people, have some form of mental illness. At least 40 million people in India suffer from anxiety. 

While we cannot control mental illnesses, recovery and prevention are choices we must make. Our next project works on the same principle. @wello.in is an audio meditation and healing mobile application where users can indulge in social community in the app itself. Here's presenting a brilliant app that we developed an app that lets you heal and meditate from the comfort of your home with just a click.

Swipe to read more about our journey. â¡ï¸

Read the full case study by clicking on the link in our bio.

Caption:
ğŸ’« I donâ€™t take action unless I am in alignment. Unless it feels right. And sometimes I'm not. And sometimes, it doesnâ€™t.  And sometimes, I donâ€™t know what the next right step is. 

So I have to sit and wait. Sitting and waiting does not sit well with me. Both of them make me uncomfortable. 
Like I should be doing more. 
Or at least be doing something.

But what I am starting to realise is that when we are in a period of waiting, itâ€™s so much more about being, and so much less about doing. 
Being in the moment. Being present. 
In the discomfort. 
In the listening. 
In the lesson. 
In the learning. 

And less about doing the action. 
About making it happen.  About moving forward.

Sometimes the best thing to do in these moments is just to sit. 
And rest. 
And listen. 
And be silent. 
And be still. 
And be present. 
And just be. 

Easier said than done, right? 
I know. Believe me, I know. 
But letâ€™s try it together. 
If youâ€™re in a season of waiting, letâ€™s embrace the waiting.  Letâ€™s stop worrying about what comes next and just enjoy what is right now. In front of you. 

Maybe instead of feeling uncomfortable, the waiting could feel like peace. Let it warms up to you. Let it come to you naturally. Perhaps, you might like it. You might warm up to it. It steadies the mind and shows you the paths ahead. And what needs to be done. 

Find your seat and sit in stillness. In silence. ğŸ’«ğŸ™ğŸ¾

Caption:
As days grow shorter and autumn hues give way to winter greys in the Northern Hemisphere, this Sunday marks the dawn of a season of yearning that many Jesus-followers call Advent.

Long ago Mary began her long journey to Jerusalem with Joseph to oblige their stateâ€™s census while growing the life of Emmanuel (God-with-us) within her.

Now, we attend to lifeâ€™s obligations while carrying hoped-for Divine deep within us, culminating in our collective celebration of the Christmas season.

But how do we move from lifeâ€™s hidden gestation to birth?

Can we enter this season without spiritually disassociating?

Oftentimes, Advent is framed as a contest between â€˜daybreakâ€™ and â€˜darkness,â€™ resisting the night to usher in the light.Â 

But perhaps the way we receive the blessings latent in this Advent season is not to chase away the darkness that we would hide, deny, & repress in ourselves and our current circumstancesâ€”but instead to embrace it.

Jung concurred, allegedly saying â€œWhat you resist, persists. What you embrace, dissolves.â€Â 

The Messiah whose advent we first anticipated would grow from his nurture in Maryâ€™s dark womb to being a counter-cultural figure with powerful guidance that bucked the prevailing wisdom of his day. While his own brother James would teach the conventional path of â€œresist the devil and he will flee from you,â€ Jesus advocated for embrace:

â€œMake friends with your Adversary quickly while you are together on the way, so your opponent may not hand you over to the judge, and the judge to the officer, and you be thrown into prison.â€ (Matt 5:25)

Can we cease demonizing the darkness?

Can we hold our shadows close this Advent?Â 

Iâ€™d like to try. And Iâ€™d like this effort to be beautiful. So Iâ€™ve teamed up with my dear friend and colleague @ourladyofperpetualbliss â€” a gifted poet, scholar and preacherâ€”to give us a guided meditation we can immerse ourselves in, right now.

Jennifer invites us into the grand story of Incarnation â€”imaginally placing ourselves in the energies of Mother and Child. Please give yourself a few minutes to unite the Divine Darkness and Holy Light within yourself in this rich audio meditation, link in bio.

Caption:
Take a moment to stop and breathe.

Notice that when you struggle, strive, fight, reach, grasp or force your mind, you push away the peace you seek. 

And the moment you stop, soften the mind, relax your body, cease striving, and give up the struggle, the peace you seek is already here as a significant presence of an effortless being. 

The very nature of grace is effortless ease. It is already wholly complete, whole, free, vast, and open.

It intrinsically knows how to care for every aspect of your life and is always in flow.

Like a river flowing over water-smoothed rocks, it has a natural ease.

Yet itâ€™s as if no one is doing the doing or â€˜flowing the flow.â€™ It just is. 

It is simultaneously supremely restful and scintillatingly alive: it loves to give birth to creation. This flow knows the proper action in each moment.

Take a moment to stop and breathe today with the free audio meditation from Brandon.

If you are new to meditation or want to create a more consistent mindfulness practice and increase your self-awareness, then this meditation challenge is for you!

The idea for this challenge came to be during a deep yoga session... and just a few weeks later, it was born! 

The challenge consists of 3 daily guided meditations (including breathing exercises) designed to help wake up, energize, and restore your body:

â˜€ï¸ Morning â€” WAKE UP + GROUND
10-minute energy-boosting, grounding & balancing meditation to begin your day on an intentional and anxiety-free note.

âœ¨ Afternoon â€” CHECK IN + CONNECT
10-minute energizing, focus-enhancing & stress relieving meditation to reconnect during the day.

ğŸŒ™ Night â€” REST + REFLECT 
7-minute meditation to help you reflect, rest, and digest at the end of the day.

The goal is to complete these three meditations every day for at least 5 days (I recommend at least 2 weeks if you are new to meditating/breathwork and want to get in the habit of creating a consistent daily practice).

Caption:
Summertime is upon us!  And as the days stretch longer, the sun shines brighter and hotter, and our energy levels gets a reboot, we're celebrating the lightness and luminosity of the summer season.

June 21st- September 6th 

Each week beginning June 21 (Summer Solstice), you will receive a simple meditation to continue and sustain your meditation practice through the summer months.

Details:

o Investment in your meditation practice: $27
o From June 21 through September 6, you will receive a brief meditation (10-15 minutes) accompanied by a poem in your Inbox
o This series offers 13 weekly meditations which will include honoring celestial happenings
o The recorded meditations can be downloaded to your favorite device and listened to at your convenience.
o The meditations will be sent the morning of the scheduled day.
o You will have regular access to your teacher, Judy Bousquin.
o Resources will be included when available 
o The meditations are meant to offer healing and support for personal awareness and growth.
o Bonus: take your meditation practice with you wherever you go this summer!

Caption: How is everyone doing? Ive been thinking about failure this week and how human beings perceive failure, often with great fear and trepidation but I believe it can wind up being a beautiful thing. It makes us wait longer and work on our ideas and the reasoning behind them. It helps us to mature. We don't live on a promise of a possible destination and the compass has a habit of altering course mid step. Work often takes years and years to get into production. This is why it is soo fundamentally important for us to really truly be in love with the thing. This is the story of how an eight minute film about a lonely satellite fix it guy took thirteen years to get made.\n\n#shortfilm #filmpodcast #audiomeditation #lostinspace #cosmicdrama

Caption:
8 cups of calm â˜•ï¸

In this practice, we connect to sound in an intentional way. In the full-length audio, I mention that we may have very different breathing rates so if we are not in sync, that is completely okay - hum at your pace without judgment. Also, if for any reason gently plugging the ears (lightly pressing on the tragus) feels triggering as the sound intensifies, unplug and practice with the ears open. If youâ€™d like to get creative, let your voice and body play!

[one-minute-transcript: *chime* As you begin to settle into a space of ease, listen for a few moments to the sounds around you. Capture what you hear and let it be.
Now, create a few open-mouth exhales, shifting your attention to sounds made by your body. Now, we will add in another layer of sound by humming.]

Caption:
Meditations from King Island

Nature does not hurry, yet everything is accomplished - L.Tzu

Hari Om Yogis.

We are pleased to release a series of meditations we have been working on whilst living in King Island.
Inspired by the environment, this NEW audio series is designed for you to develop a regular meditation practice.
Each meditation is a different journey inward where you will learn to calm your mind, steady your nervous system & develop a more integrated, peaceful and calm state of being.

In this series we teach you 5 unique meditation techniques.

1. Earth Meditation (15min):

Caption:
Just a couple of years ago we never could've imagined that the world would be in the shape it's in. Everyone wants to do the right thing in order for things to "go back to normal". The problem is that they won't â€“ and theyÂ can't. Expressed as the myriad ofÂ different facets in theÂ kaleidoscope of current events, what should be undeniable to anyone despite their vantage point, is that we are living through a very important transitional period in the evolution of our collective consciousness. It's going to be a wild ride and we are just getting started.Â â€©Â â€©As a man, a brother, a son, a partner, a trauma survivor, and as someone who has vowed to protect and help others, the questions haveÂ always been: "What can I do? What is within my control and how can I offer assistance to the people around me? How can I offer my medicine in a way that is useful, accessible, and easy to assimilate?" Looking for answers to these questions, I have spent the past two years structuring and refining a way to share a system to improve what I consider to be the most crucial and often overlooked aspect of healing: self-regulation.Â â €
â €
You see, when I trace the myriad of issues that we are currently facing back to the single most important thing to focus on, what I find is not science. It's not politics. It's not media. It's not tech. What I find is the ability to modulate our emotions and our nervous system. Because a dysregulated nervous system can't bear true health, can't make the best choices, can'tÂ access intuitive wisdom, and most importantly, can't listen to a different point of view with true compassion and understanding. And if we can't all learn to come together at this pivotal point in history, things are going to get much crazier than they already are.Â â €
â €
With this in mind, I am excited to invite you to the inauguralÂ live course forÂ Unmuzzle Your Power Animal, an embodiment practice that combines shamanism, meditation, breathwork, bodybuilding, yoga, tactical psychology, trauma theory, neuroscience, and emotional release techniques, presented as a powerful integrated system designed for radical self-regulation.â €
â €

Did you know that today is World Meditation Day?

It took me a very long time to appreciate the wonder that is Meditation (Dhyana) my mind was ALWAYS busy, it would never ever stop! Some were nice thoughts but more often that not they were self-sabotaging. Meditation didn't come naturally for me, I was always thinking about my to-do lists, what I was having for dinner, the noises in the background, that itch that I needed to scratch and then the sitting still which was so excruciating. Not to mention the insects that would land on me! Trust me, meditation does not have to be like this.

If you haven't already taken me up on my free relaxing audio meditation why not give it a go today. If you already have (thank you!), I have added another one for you to have a listen too, this one is an energising one.

Choose which ever suits your mood right now or whenever is convenient to you.

Caption:
âœ¨Make the most of the lighter mornings and try a walking meditationâœ¨

This week as part of our 30 day â€˜Revive Your Morningsâ€™ challenge were encouraging our members to make the most of the lighter mornings and try a walking meditationğŸ™ŒğŸ». Walking meditation is an active practice that requires you to be consciously aware and moving in the environment rather than sitting down with your eyes closed. Itâ€™s a simple form of meditation that can be particularly valuable for beginners or anyone who prefers a more active form of this practiceğŸ’•.Â 

But why is it valuable to add a walking meditation to your morning routineğŸ¤”?

1.It Provides a Sense of Perspective - Taking a walk outdoors can break you out of a mental fog
2.It Helps You Connect to the Present Moment - As you walk and become increasingly aware, the mind grows quieter.
3.It Helps You Get to Know Your BodyğŸ’•

Mindful walking is about taking your time, all the time you need. Remember, it isnâ€™t about how fast you go, but how deeply you can feel. To support our members, @jennystewartyoga has recorded a 10 minute walking meditation. Give yourself a moment to just be. Letâ€™s not miss all the beauty that surrounds us and remember the wander of this journey we call life.

Didnâ€™t take part, donâ€™t worry you can join the Online Studio and start the challenge at anytime - itâ€™s full of daily tips, advice, challenges, exclusive breakfast recipes and classes best completed in the morningğŸŒ! 

PLUS coming soon on the Online Studioâ€¦.Power-UP MayğŸ’¥!

There are a lot of myths around hypnosis. 

A trained hypnotist or hypnotherapist induces a state of intense concentration or focused attention. This is a guided process with verbal cues and repetition. The state you enter may appear similar to sleep in many ways. 

âŒYou are ALWAYS fully aware of what is going on. 

âŒYou DO NOT lose control over your behaviour while under hypnosis.

âŒYou remain aware of and remember what happens during hypnosis.

People typically describe the feeling of being hypnotised as being in a calm, physically, and mentally relaxed state. In this state, you are able to focus deeply on what you are thinking about.

Hypnotherapy is particularly good for depression to enhance an overall sense of well-being, lift mood, and boost feelings of hopefulness.

I am a trained Clinical Hypnotherapist and in my online programs, I create audio meditations, to compliment the written work, which you can listen to at any time during the day, before you fall asleep and whilst asleep. 
 
These audio meditations will offer suggestions to your subconscious mind to help you to think more positively and uplift your sense of happiness and wellbeing.

Please note, at NO time listening to these audio meditations will you run around the room like a chicken clucking!!! ğŸ˜‚ğŸ˜‚ğŸ¤£

â€¢ Loneliness - Accepting our emotions without fear or judgement.

Caption:
Iâ€™m so happy! The reviews for my audio meditation came in! 

These feedbacks are exactly WHY I recorded the meditation in the first place and it is what inspired the script for Stepping Into Your Greatness meditation. 

[If you havenâ€™t downloaded yet, itâ€™s on my website www.intuitwithjessie.com]

I was often asked where did I learn and how do I know how to meditate? 

In this lifetime, my first experience was taught by a Buddhist monk in a temple. It was just me and the cement floor, no fan, in the tropical weather for one hot hour. First time, and I sat through it 60 minutes when everyone else had already left the room. He said Iâ€™ve done this before. 

10 years later, I started receiving visions of myself. 

Many lifetimes ago, I was a male monk in Tibet in the 1600 AD. I saw myself as a 5â€™2â€ small framed, dark skin, very skinny young man who came out of the monastery to explore enlightenment on his own. Once a week, he will take a few hours walk to a nearby village town to ask for food and then retrieve back the small cave up in the mountain and meditate. In winter times, he meditated there the whole of 4 months without food and kept his body warm through the frigid temperature. 

I didnâ€™t know surviving the winter months with a robe was possible until recently, I chanced upon a Youtube documentary of monks using a yoga technique to enter a state of deep meditation and significantly raise their body heat known as â€˜g Tum-moâ€™. 

I was shocked! Yes, I still get shocked with my own ability sometimes. 

And also, now I know why I sweat when I meditate. 

This is how the knowledge and techniques of meditation came naturally to me. It helps when I learn more and I get to remember how I did it in the psat. As I learned, I tweaked it to our modern lifestyle so that it is easier to â€˜digestâ€™. 

My goal is that everyone experience some kind of peace in a day, even if itâ€™s just 10 minutes â€” Youâ€™ll be much better off. 

Have you tried the audio meditation? Would love to hear your thought. 

[Download at www.intuitiwithjessie.com]

How My Meditation Journey Started
.
My meditation journey started when I wholeheartedly fell involve with practicing yoga three years ago, although it has always been present in my life. Remembering myself as a child staying at my grandparentsâ€™ house, my grandmother would practice yoga every morning. She had a thick book about yoga and meditation, and I would flick through the pages, curiously observing each picture of all the different poses whilst my grandmother would lay in Savasana pose, kindly encouraging for silence if I began to ask too many questions. Now I understand! Yoga and meditation have allowed me to grow and transform not only my body but my thoughts and habits in ways that I did not think possible. During this time, I began to explore a wide array of therapeutic sessions ranging from Tibetan healing bowls, aromatherapy, breath-work, and crystal meditations. Soon after, I decided to open up my own platform focused on meditation and mindfulness for others to join along with me to simply slow down their mind. I strongly believe pure happiness is achieved when you stop waiting for life to begin and start making the most of the moment you are in. Taking one day at a time.
.

.
This practice guides you to pay particularly close attention to the sensations of the breath. Observing the very start of an inhale and following all the way to the very end of an exhale. This practice allows you not only to acknowledge your object of focus â€” the breath â€”, but also the entire process of it. This mindfulness meditation encourages you to adapt the skill of conscious awareness â€” we simply stay with what is. You will learn how to remain aware of when you drift away and get caught in thoughts that are anywhere but right here and right now. It is in our natural nature to grab at thoughts, but when you will get into a habit of mindful awareness, you will be able to observe your thoughts and feelings without judging them. Caption:
What is meditation?
.
There are different ways to meditate, and since it's such a personal practice, there are probably more than any of us know about. There are a couple that is usually focused on heavily in scientific research, though. These are focused-attention, or mindful meditation, where you focus on one specific thing: your breathing, a sensation in your body, or a particular object outside of you. The point of this type of meditation is to focus intensely on one topic and continually bring your attention back to that focal point when it wanders.
The other type of meditation that's often used in research is open-monitoring meditation. This is where you pay attention to all of the things happening around youâ€”you notice everything without reacting.
.

Caption:
*NEW BLOG POST* Have you heard of Binaural Beats? It is a sound technology that can be used to help facilitate specific brain wave states.

How can a binaural beat help us hack our brain wave state? A binaural beat simply means playing two different frequencies at the same time in a different ear. Binaural beats require a stereo audio interface, typically a pair of stereo headphones. What does "stereo" mean? It simply means that there is a left and right audio channel that can play independently of each other. When listening to a binaural beat, you hear one frequency in either the left or right ear and a slightly different frequency in the other ear. Through a process called "entrainment", the brain tries to reconcile the slight difference in frequency and over time can actually begin to oscillate at the DIFFERENCE in the two frequencies. 

In the example image above, a frequency of 40 Hz is played in the left ear and a frequency of 50 Hz is played in the right. The brain hears these differences in frequency (which is 10 Hz) and wants to "reconcile" the difference by beginning to migrate it's own frequency to that difference. What is 10 Hz in brain wave states? It is the Alpha state, associated with activating the parasympathetic nervous system and relaxation!

**CHECK OUT MY BLOG FOR THE FULL ARTICLE! (Link in Bio)** I will have some binaural beat tracks coming out really soon for your listening pleasure! 

Have you listened to binaural beats? What has your experience been with them?

Caption:
Can the work of an artistâ€™s hands help you encounter God? I believe it can. 

Visio divina means â€œdivine seeingâ€ in Latin, as we gaze upon a work of art and experience Godâ€™s presence through it.

It engages the eye and the imagination. You can do it with a piece of art, religious or not, or even a leaf or landscape you discover outside. If you are visual, as so many of us are today, then visio divina can be a refreshing way to experience God.

Artist Tim Mooney says of visio divina: "It invites us to be seen, addressed, surprised, and transformed by God who is never limited or tied to any image, but speaks through them.â€

Using a piece called Rainbow Hands from the book A Cloud of Outrageous Blue by Vesper Stamper, I lead a 10-minute visio divina exercise on the podcast this week. It's an amazing piece of art that may just remind you who God made you to be as a creative person.

Listen via my profile, and there's a special link to the piece in the shownotes.
